itical parties in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Progressive parties]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Socialist parties in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "Pppenipusi8696", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added more stuff)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Workers%27_Party_(Singapore)"}
{"title_page": "Iris M. Ovshinsky", "text_new": "{{short description|American businesswoman and scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Iris M. Ovshinsky\n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1927|7|13}}\n| birth_place       = [[New York City]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2006|8|16|1927|7|13}} \n| death_place       = [[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan]]\n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = \n| alma_mater        =  Bachelor's degree, zoology, [[Swarthmore College]], 1947; master's degree, biology, [[University of Michigan]], 1950; doctorate, biochemistry, from Boston University, 1960\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = 1960\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Co-founding [[Energy Conversion Devices]] with her husband \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = Andrew Dibner, [[Stanford R. Ovshinsky]]\n}}\n\n'''Iris M. Ovshinsky''' (July 13, 1927&nbsp;\u2013 August 16, 2006) was an American businesswoman and scientist, and the co-founder of [[Energy Conversion Devices]] with her husband [[Stanford R. Ovshinsky]], serving as its Vice President from its founding in 1960 until her death.\n\nBorn Iris L. Miroy in [[New York City]], she earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[zoology]]<ref>Rossiter, Joe. [http://www.redorbit.com/news/business/623486/iris_ovshinsky_partner_in_energy_life/index.html Iris Ovshinsky: Partner in Energy, Life] ''Detroit Free Press'', 2006-08-19. Retrieved on 2007-08-08.</ref> from [[Swarthmore College]] in 1947, a [[master's degree]] in [[biology]] from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1950, and [[doctorate]] in [[biochemistry]] in 1960<ref name=\"bu\">McNeil, Taylor. [http://www.bu.edu/alumni/bostonia/2001/fall/profiles/energetic/index.html A Couple of Energetic Accomplishments] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301103905/http://www.bu.edu/alumni/bostonia/2001/fall/profiles/energetic/index.html |date=2007-03-01 }} Fall 2001. Retrieved on 2007-08-08.</ref> from [[Boston University]].\n\nShe was first married to Andrew Dibner, with whom she had a son, Steven, and a daughter, Robin. Following her 1959 divorce from Dibner, she married Ovshinsky in 1962; the marriage brought her three stepsons, Ben, Harvey, and Dale. Mr. Ovshinsky was a [[List of prolific inventors|prolific inventor]], credited with inventing the [[nickel metal hydride battery]], and [[Amorphous solid|amorphous materials]] used in a variety of products from flexible solar panels to rewritable CDs and DVDs. Disagreeing with his wife's downplaying of her contributions throughout their careers, Stan said she was a partner in everything they did, \"a colleague and collaborator in my scientific activity. She's just too damn modest.\"<ref name=\"bu\" />\n\nOvshinsky briefly appears in [[Who Killed the Electric Car?]] the documentary film which explores the creation, limited commercialization, and subsequent destruction of the battery electric vehicle in the United States, specifically the General Motors EV1 of the 1990s.\n\nOvshinsky died on August 16, 2006, aged 79, having suffered a [[myocardial infarction]] while swimming near her home in [[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan]].<ref name=\"NYT 20060905\">{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|title=Iris M. Ovshinsky, 79, Partner in Cleaner Auto Technology, Is Dead|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/05/business/05ovshinsky.html?ex=1315108800&en=d3c9f314ba88ac69&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&_r=0|accessdate=2012-10-19|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 5, 2006|page=Business section}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ovshinsky, Iris M.}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomfield, Oakland County, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businesswoman and scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Iris M. Ovshinsky\n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1927|7|13}}\n| birth_place       = [[New York City]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2006|8|16|1927|7|13}} \n| death_place       = [[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan]]\n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = \n| alma_mater        =  Bachelor's degree, zoology, [[Swarthmore College]], 1947; master's degree, biology, [[University of Michigan]], 1950; doctorate, biochemistry, from Boston University, 1960\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = 1960\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Co-founding [[Energy Conversion Devices]] with her husband \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = Andrew Dibner, [[Stanford R. Ovshinsky]]\n}}\n\n'''Iris M. Ovshinsky''' (July 13, 1927&nbsp;\u2013 August 16, 2006) was an American businesswoman and scientist, and the co-founder of [[Energy Conversion Devices]] with her husband [[Stanford R. Ovshinsky]], serving as its Vice President from its founding in 1960 until her death.\n\nBorn Iris L. Miroy in [[New York City]], she earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[zoology]]<ref>Rossiter, Joe. [http://www.redorbit.com/news/business/623486/iris_ovshinsky_partner_in_energy_life/index.html Iris Ovshinsky: Partner in Energy, Life] ''Detroit Free Press'', 2006-08-19. Retrieved on 2007-08-08.</ref> from [[Swarthmore College]] in 1947, a [[master's degree]] in [[biology]] from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1950, and [[doctorate]] in [[biochemistry]] in 1960<ref name=\"bu\">McNeil, Taylor. [http://www.bu.edu/alumni/bostonia/2001/fall/profiles/energetic/index.html A Couple of Energetic Accomplishments] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301103905/http://www.bu.edu/alumni/bostonia/2001/fall/profiles/energetic/index.html |date=2007-03-01 }} Fall 2001. Retrieved on 2007-08-08.</ref> from [[Boston University]].\n\nShe was first married to Andrew Dibner, with whom she had a son, Steven, and a daughter, Robin. Following her 1959 divorce from Dibner, she married Ovshinsky in 1962; the marriage brought her three stepsons, Ben, Harvey, and Dale. Mr. Ovshinsky was a [[List of prolific inventors|prolific inventor]], credited with inventing the [[nickel metal hydride battery]], and [[Amorphous solid|amorphous materials]] used in a variety of products from flexible solar panels to rewritable CDs and DVDs. Disagreeing with his wife's downplaying of her contributions throughout their careers, Stan said she was a partner in everything they did, \"a colleague and collaborator in my scientific activity. She's just too damn modest.\"<ref name=\"bu\" />\n\nOvshinsky briefly appears in [[Who Killed the Electric Car?]] the documentary film which explores the creation, limited commercialization, and subsequent destruction of the battery electric vehicle in the United States, specifically the General Motors EV1 of the 1990s.\n\nOvshinsky died on August 16, 2006, aged 79, having suffered a [[myocardial infarction]] while swimming near her home in [[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan]].<ref name=\"NYT 20060905\">{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|title=Iris M. Ovshinsky, 79, Partner in Cleaner Auto Technology, Is Dead|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/05/business/05ovshinsky.html?ex=1315108800&en=d3c9f314ba88ac69&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&_r=0|accessdate=2012-10-19|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 5, 2006|page=Business section}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ovshinsky, Iris M.}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomfield, Oakland County, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iris_M._Ovshinsky"}
{"title_page": "Simard Lake (Petit-M\u00e9catina)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Simard|Simard Lake}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Simard Lake\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Petit-M\u00e9catina, Quebec|Petit-M\u00e9catina]] / [[Kegaska, Quebec|Kegaska]], [[Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]\n| coords = {{Coord|50|17|24|N|61|20|29|W|region:CA-QC_type:waterbody_source:CGNDB|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow =\n| outflow =River\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = Canada\n| length = {{convert|12.2|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1.8|km|abbr=on}}\n| area = {{convert|NNNN|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = \n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|32|m|abbr=on}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n'''Simard Lake''' is a freshwater body of the unorganized territory of [[Petit-M\u00e9catina, Quebec|Petit-M\u00e9catina]] and the municipality of [[Kegaska]], in the [[Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]], in the administrative region of [[C\u00f4te-Nord]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], in [[Canada]].\n\nThe maps of this area do not indicate a road suitable for vehicles in this area. However, [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]] which runs along the northwest shore of the Gulf of St. Lawrence, passes {{convert|7.3|km}} from the south bay of Lake Simard.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe main hydrographic slopes near Lake Simard are:\n* north side: [[Katshiputiskamatunant Lake]], [[Grand Priant Lake]], [[Musquaro River]], Mistahiniu lake;\n* east side: Musquaro River, [[Kegaska Bay]];\n* south side: [[Anse Muddy River]], [[Kegaska River]], [[Belley River]];\n* west side: [[Kegaska Lake]], Kegaska River.\n\nWith a length of {{convert|12.2|km}}, Lake Simard has a misshapen outline with several bays, islands and peninsulas. Lake Simard stretches like a large misshapen M overturned on the left.\n\nLac Simard is located north of a large swamp region that covers an area between the north shore of the Gulf of St. Lawrence and Lake Kegaska; this marsh area stretches east to the Musquaro River. The mouth of Lake Simard is located at the bottom of a bay southeast of the lake, either:\n\n* {{convert|7.1|km}} east of the mouth of [[Kegaska Lake]];\n* {{convert|9.5|km}} north-west of the village center of [[Kegaska]];\n* {{convert|10.4|km}} north-west of the mouth of the outlet of Lake Simard;\n\nFrom the mouth of Lake Simard, the current flows for {{convert|15.7|km}} towards the Southeast following the course of a river (outlet of Lake Simard) to a sub-bay of K\u00e9gaska Bay.\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe term \"Simard\" is a family name of French origin.\n\nThe toponym \"Lac Simard\" was formalized on December 5, 1968 by the [[Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec]].<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/Fiche.aspx?no_seq=59712 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: \"Lac Simard\".]</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gulf of St. Lawrence]], a body of water\n* [[Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[Petit-M\u00e9catina, Quebec|Petit-M\u00e9catina]], a [[unorganized territory]]\n* [[Kegaska]], a [[municipality]]\n* [[List of lakes of Canada]]\n\n{{Portal|lakes and rivers|C\u00f4te-Nord}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simard, lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of C\u00f4te-Nord]]\n[[Category:Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Simard|Simard Lake}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Simard Lake\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Petit-M\u00e9catina, Quebec|Petit-M\u00e9catina]] / [[Kegaska, Quebec|Kegaska]], [[Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]\n| coords = {{Coord|50|17|24|N|61|20|29|W|region:CA-QC_type:waterbody_source:CGNDB|display=inline,title}}\n| type = \n| inflow =\n| outflow =River\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = Canada\n| length = {{convert|12.2|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1.8|km|abbr=on}}\n| area = {{convert|NNNN|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = \n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|32|m|abbr=on}}\n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n'''Simard Lake''' is a freshwater body of the unorganized territory of [[Petit-M\u00e9catina, Quebec|Petit-M\u00e9catina]] and the municipality of [[Kegaska]], in the [[Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]], in the administrative region of [[C\u00f4te-Nord]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], in Canada]].\n\nThe maps of this area do not indicate a road suitable for vehicles in this area. However, [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]] which runs along the northwest shore of the Gulf of St. Lawrence, passes {{convert|7.3|km}} from the south bay of Lake Simard.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe main hydrographic slopes near Lake Simard are:\n* north side: [[Katshiputiskamatunant Lake]], [[Grand Priant Lake]], [[Musquaro River]], Mistahiniu lake;\n* east side: Musquaro River, [[Kegaska Bay]];\n* south side: [[Anse Muddy River]], [[Kegaska River]], [[Belley River]];\n* west side: [[Kegaska Lake]], Kegaska River.\n\nWith a length of {{convert|12.2|km}}, Lake Simard has a misshapen outline with several bays, islands and peninsulas. Lake Simard stretches like a large misshapen M overturned on the left.\n\nLac Simard is located north of a large swamp region that covers an area between the north shore of the Gulf of St. Lawrence and Lake Kegaska; this marsh area stretches east to the Musquaro River. The mouth of Lake Simard is located at the bottom of a bay southeast of the lake, either:\n\n* {{convert|7.1|km}} east of the mouth of [[Kegaska Lake]];\n* {{convert|9.5|km}} north-west of the village center of [[Kegaska]];\n* {{convert|10.4|km}} north-west of the mouth of the outlet of Lake Simard;\n\nFrom the mouth of Lake Simard, the current flows for {{convert|15.7|km}} towards the Southeast following the course of a river (outlet of Lake Simard) to a sub-bay of K\u00e9gaska Bay.\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe term \"Simard\" is a family name of French origin.\n\nThe toponym \"Lac Simard\" was formalized on December 5, 1968 by the [[Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec]].<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/Fiche.aspx?no_seq=59712 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: \"Lac Simard\".]</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gulf of St. Lawrence]], a body of water\n* [[Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[Petit-M\u00e9catina, Quebec|Petit-M\u00e9catina]], a [[unorganized territory]]\n* [[Kegaska]], a [[municipality]]\n* [[List of lakes of Canada]]\n\n{{Portal|lakes and rivers|C\u00f4te-Nord}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simard, lake}}\n[[Category:Lakes of C\u00f4te-Nord]]\n[[Category:Le Golfe-du-Saint-Laurent Regional County Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "Veillg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simard_Lake_(Petit-M%C3%A9catina)"}
{"title_page": "Hildegarde Howard", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Hildegarde Howard\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1901|04|03}}\n| birth_place       = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|1998|02|28|1901|04|03}}\n| death_place       = [[Laguna Hills, California]]\n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = [[Paleornithology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]]\n| alma_mater        = [[U.C. Berkeley]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisors  = [[Joseph Grinnell]]\n| academic_advisors = [[William Diller Matthew]],  [[Loye H. Miller]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Significant contributions to the field of [[paleornithology]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = [[Brewster Medal]]\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}\n[[File:Hildegarde Howard.png|thumb|Hildegarde Howard, ca. 1936 (Condor 38: 128)]]\n'''Hildegarde Howard''' (April 3, 1901 \u2013 February 28, 1998) was an American pioneer in avian paleontology.<ref name=\"biodict\">Joyce Harvey & Marilyn Ogilvie (2000), ''The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science'', Volume 1, pp.621 et seq</ref>  She was well known for her discoveries in the [[La Brea Tar Pits]], among them the [[Rancho La Brea]] eagles. In 1953, Howard became the first woman to be awarded the [[Brewster Medal]]. She was also the first woman president of the [[Southern California Academy of Sciences]].<ref name=\"LATobit\">{{cite news|first=Myrna|last= Oliver|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/04/news/mn-25457|title=Hildegarde Howard; Avian Paleontologist, Curator|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 4, 1998}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHoward was born in Washington, D.C., and moved with her parents to Los Angeles in 1906; her father was a scriptwriter and her mother a musician and composer.<ref name=\"MBPS\">Frank Perry, [http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html \"Hildegarde Howard\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083837/http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html |date=2016-03-04 }}, Monterey Bay Paleontological Society (last visited April 13, 2013).</ref>  In 1920 Howard commenced her studies at the [[Southern Branch of the University of California]] (later renamed UCLA).<ref name=\"MBPS\" />  Her first biology teacher, Pirie Davidson, inspired her to change her concentration from journalism to biology; Davidson helped her get a job working for the paleontologist [[Chester Stock]].<ref name=\"MBPS\" />  She completed her bachelor's degree at [[U.C. Berkeley]], where she took courses in [[paleontology]].<ref name=\"MBPS\" />  In 1924, Howard joined the scientific staff of the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]] part-time; her work there on the extinct turkey ''Parapavo californicus'' was credited towards her master's degree at Berkeley, where she would also earn the Ph.D. in 1928, with a dissertation on the fossil birds of the Emery Shellmound.<ref>\"Hildegarde Howard\" (obituary), ''Toledo Blade'', March 6, 1998.</ref> In 1929, Howard returned to the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]]. Named chief curator of science in 1951, she retired in 1961, but continued to conduct research and to publish on [[Evolution of birds|avian evolution]]. While at the museum and in retirement, Howard described 3 families, 13 genera, 57 species, and 2 subspecies.<ref name=\"Auk\">{{cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = Kenneth E. | last2 = Jr | year = 2000 | title = In Memoriam: Hildegarde Howard, 1901-1998 | journal = The Auk | volume = 117 | issue = 3| pages = 775\u2013779 | doi = 10.1642/0004-8038(2000)117[0775:IMHH]2.0.CO;2 | jstor = 4089601 }}</ref>\n\nHoward married Henry Anson Wylde in 1930. Wylde, who would become chief of exhibits at the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]], died in 1984.<ref name=\"MBPS\" />\n\n==Significant works==\nHoward published some 150 scientific papers over the course of her career.<ref name=\"Auk\" />\n\n* {{Citation | title = The avifauna of Emeryville shellmound | year = 1929 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = University of California Publications in Zoology | pages = 301\u2013394 | volume = 32 | issue = 2}}\n* Howard described the first \"toothed\" bird from North America and assigned the name \"Osteodontornis\" to it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Frank |title=Hildegarde Howard |url=http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html |website=Calcentral.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107133946/http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html |archivedate=7 January 2009}}{{better source|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n* {{Citation | title = Fossil Birds | year = 1962 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = Science Series | pages = 44 | volume = 17}}\n* {{Citation | title = A New Avian Fossil from Kern County, California | year = 1969 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = The Condor | pages = 68\u201369 | volume = 71 | issue = 1 | doi=10.2307/1366050| jstor = 1366050 }}\n* {{Citation | title = A review of the extinct avian genus, Mancalla | year = 1970 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = Contributions in Science | pages = 1\u201312 | volume = 203}}\n\n==Awards==\n* 1953 [[Brewster Medal]] (first woman to be awarded the Brewster Medal<ref name=\"LATobit\" />)\n* 1962 [[Guggenheim Fellow]], Earth Science<ref>[http://www.gf.org/fellows/6875-hildegarde-howard Hildegarde Howard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614174230/http://www.gf.org/fellows/6875-hildegarde-howard |date=2012-06-14 }}, John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation (last visited April 13, 2013).</ref>\n* Elected President, [[Southern California Academy of Sciences]] (first woman president<ref name=\"LATobit\" />)\n* 1977 - Honored by having Hildegarde Howard Cenozoic Hall, Southern California Academy of Sciences, named after her<ref name=\"LATobit\" />\n* 1963 - Honorary Member, Cooper Ornithological Society<ref>[http://www.cooper.org/awards_and_grants/honorary_members.htm \"Honorary Members\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509162146/http://www.cooper.org/awards_and_grants/honorary_members.htm |date=2013-05-09 }}, Cooper Ornithological Society (last visited April 13, 2013).</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further research==\n* [[Joy Harvey]] & [[Marilyn Ogilvie]] (2000), ''The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science'', Volume 1, pp.&nbsp;621 et seq\n* Campbell, Kenneth E., Jr., editor. 1980. \"Papers in Avian Paleontology Honoring Hildegarde Howard\", ''Contributions in Science: Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County'', No. 330 (Sept. 15 1970), 296 p. (Includes biographical sketches and a bibliography of her works.)\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = Kenneth E. Jr | year = 2000 | title = In Memoriam: Hildegarde Howard, 1901-1998 | journal = The Auk | volume = 117 | issue = 3| pages = 775\u2013779 | doi=10.2307/4089601| jstor = 4089601 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = Kenneth E. Jr | year = 2000 | title = Hildegarde Howard | url = | journal = Society of Vertebrate Paleontology News Bulletin | volume = 178 | issue = | pages = 131\u2013133 }}\n\n; Archives\n* Hildegarde Howard Papers, archives, [[George C. Page Museum]], Hancock Park, California\n* Hildegarde Howard Papers, archives, [[Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County]], Los Angeles, California\n* Chester Stock Papers, [[George C. Page Museum]], Hancock Park, Museum\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://nhm.giftplans.org/index.php?cID=111 Hildegarde Howard Society], Los Angeles County Natural History Museum\n* [https://twitter.com/SciOfMotherhood/status/311894875270438913/photo/1 Science of Motherhood] (photo)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard, Hildegarde}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:American ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Women ornithologists]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:American paleontologists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:20th-century zoologists]]\n[[Category:Women paleontologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Hildegarde Howard\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')-->\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1901|04|03}}\n| birth_place       = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|1998|02|28|1901|04|03}}\n| death_place       = [[Laguna Hills, California]]\n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = [[Paleornithology]]\n| workplaces        = [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]]\n| alma_mater        = [[U.C. Berkeley]]\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisors  = [[Joseph Grinnell]]\n| academic_advisors = [[William Diller Matthew]],  [[Loye H. Miller]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Significant contributions to the field of [[paleornithology]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = [[Brewster Medal]]\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}\n[[File:Hildegarde Howard.png|thumb|Hildegarde Howard, ca. 1936 (Condor 38: 128)]]\n'''Hildegarde Howard''' (April 3, 1901 \u2013 February 28, 1998) was an American pioneer in avian paleontology.<ref name=\"biodict\">Joyce Harvey & Marilyn Ogilvie (2000), ''The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science'', Volume 1, pp.621 et seq</ref>  She was well known for her discoveries in the [[La Brea Tar Pits]], among them the [[Rancho La Brea]] eagles. In 1953, Howard became the first woman to be awarded the [[Brewster Medal]]. She was also the first woman president of the [[Southern California Academy of Sciences]].<ref name=\"LATobit\">{{cite news|first=Myrna|last= Oliver|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/04/news/mn-25457|title=Hildegarde Howard; Avian Paleontologist, Curator|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 4, 1998}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHoward was born in Washington, D.C., and moved with her parents to Los Angeles in 1906; her father was a scriptwriter and her mother a musician and composer.<ref name=\"MBPS\">Frank Perry, [http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html \"Hildegarde Howard\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083837/http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html |date=2016-03-04 }}, Monterey Bay Paleontological Society (last visited April 13, 2013).</ref>  In 1920 Howard commenced her studies at the [[Southern Branch of the University of California]] (later renamed UCLA).<ref name=\"MBPS\" />  Her first biology teacher, Pirie Davidson, inspired her to change her concentration from journalism to biology; Davidson helped her get a job working for the paleontologist [[Chester Stock]].<ref name=\"MBPS\" />  She completed her bachelor's degree at [[U.C. Berkeley]], where she took courses in [[paleontology]].<ref name=\"MBPS\" />  In 1924, Howard joined the scientific staff of the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]] part-time; her work there on the extinct turkey ''Parapavo californicus'' was credited towards her master's degree at Berkeley, where she would also earn the Ph.D. in 1928, with a dissertation on the fossil birds of the Emery Shellmound.<ref>\"Hildegarde Howard\" (obituary), ''Toledo Blade'', March 6, 1998.</ref> In 1929, Howard returned to the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]]. Named chief curator of science in 1951, she retired in 1961, but continued to conduct research and to publish on [[Evolution of birds|avian evolution]]. While at the museum and in retirement, Howard described 3 families, 13 genera, 57 species, and 2 subspecies.<ref name=\"Auk\">{{cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = Kenneth E. | last2 = Jr | year = 2000 | title = In Memoriam: Hildegarde Howard, 1901-1998 | journal = The Auk | volume = 117 | issue = 3| pages = 775\u2013779 | doi = 10.1642/0004-8038(2000)117[0775:IMHH]2.0.CO;2 | jstor = 4089601 }}</ref>\n\nHoward married Henry Anson Wylde in 1930. Wylde, who would become chief of exhibits at the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History]], died in 1984.<ref name=\"MBPS\" />\n\n==Significant works==\nHoward published some 150 scientific papers over the course of her career.<ref name=\"Auk\" />\n\n* {{Citation | title = The avifauna of Emeryville shellmound | year = 1929 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = University of California Publications in Zoology | pages = 301\u2013394 | volume = 32 | issue = 2}}\n* Howard described the first \"toothed\" bird from North America and assigned the name \"Osteodontornis\" to it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Frank |title=Hildegarde Howard |url=http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html |website=Calcentral.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107133946/http://www.calcentral.com/~fossils/peopled.html |archivedate=7 January 2009}}{{better source|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n* {{Citation | title = Fossil Birds | year = 1962 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = Science Series | pages = 44 | volume = 17}}\n* {{Citation | title = A New Avian Fossil from Kern County, California | year = 1969 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = The Condor | pages = 68\u201369 | volume = 71 | issue = 1 | doi=10.2307/1366050| jstor = 1366050 }}\n* {{Citation | title = A review of the extinct avian genus, Mancalla | year = 1970 | author = Howard, Hildegarde | journal = Contributions in Science | pages = 1\u201312 | volume = 203}}\n\n==Awards==\n* 1953 [[Brewster Medal]] (first woman to be awarded the Brewster Medal<ref name=\"LATobit\" />)\n* 1962 [[Guggenheim Fellow]], Earth Science<ref>[http://www.gf.org/fellows/6875-hildegarde-howard Hildegarde Howard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614174230/http://www.gf.org/fellows/6875-hildegarde-howard |date=2012-06-14 }}, John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation (last visited April 13, 2013).</ref>\n* Elected President, [[Southern California Academy of Sciences]] (first woman president<ref name=\"LATobit\" />)\n* 1977 - Honored by having Hildegarde Howard Cenozoic Hall, Southern California Academy of Sciences, named after her<ref name=\"LATobit\" />\n* 1963 - Honorary Member, Cooper Ornithological Society<ref>[http://www.cooper.org/awards_and_grants/honorary_members.htm \"Honorary Members\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509162146/http://www.cooper.org/awards_and_grants/honorary_members.htm |date=2013-05-09 }}, Cooper Ornithological Society (last visited April 13, 2013).</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further research==\n* [[Joy Harvey]] & [[Marilyn Ogilvie]] (2000), ''The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science'', Volume 1, pp.&nbsp;621 et seq\n* Campbell, Kenneth E., Jr., editor. 1980. \"Papers in Avian Paleontology Honoring Hildegarde Howard\", ''Contributions in Science: Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County'', No. 330 (Sept. 15 1970), 296 p. (Includes biographical sketches and a bibliography of her works.)\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = Kenneth E. Jr | year = 2000 | title = In Memoriam: Hildegarde Howard, 1901-1998 | journal = The Auk | volume = 117 | issue = 3| pages = 775\u2013779 | doi=10.2307/4089601| jstor = 4089601 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = Kenneth E. Jr | year = 2000 | title = Hildegarde Howard | url = | journal = Society of Vertebrate Paleontology News Bulletin | volume = 178 | issue = | pages = 131\u2013133 }}\n\n; Archives\n* Hildegarde Howard Papers, archives, [[George C. Page Museum]], Hancock Park, California\n* Hildegarde Howard Papers, archives, [[Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County]], Los Angeles, California\n* Chester Stock Papers, [[George C. Page Museum]], Hancock Park, Museum\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://nhm.giftplans.org/index.php?cID=111 Hildegarde Howard Society], Los Angeles County Natural History Museum\n* [https://twitter.com/SciOfMotherhood/status/311894875270438913/photo/1 Science of Motherhood] (photo)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard, Hildegarde}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:American ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Women ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:American paleontologists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:People from Los Angeles]]\n